}
In this example, the  operator is used to access the  function that exists within , which is nested under . This encapsulates your code, preventing name collisions and promoting organization.Understanding the  OperatorOn the other hand, the  operator is commonly used for accessing fields and methods from an instance of a struct or enum. This operator is essential for working with object-oriented concepts like methods and properties in Rust.Example Usage of the  OperatorHere's how you can use the  operator in a practical example:struct Person {
    name: String,
    age: u32,
}

impl Person {
    fn new(name: String, age: u32) -> Person {
        Person { name, age }
